- www.addic7ed.com -

04:13.127 --> 04:15.129
[♪♪♪]

04:19.676 --> 04:23.888
You know, I never understood
the concept of renewing vows.

04:24.055 --> 04:27.809
- Why? I think it's sweet.
- Yeah, but unnecessary. No offense.

04:28.017 --> 04:30.019
- No offense taken.
- Offense taken.

04:30.853 --> 04:34.357
- I suppose you're gonna tell us why.
- Please, don't be getting him started.

04:34.524 --> 04:38.611
Too late. Since marriages
never expire, it's like...

04:38.778 --> 04:42.366
going to the DMV, and
taking a driving test

04:42.367 --> 04:43.759
when you already have your license.

04:43.783 --> 04:45.493
- Seriously, Mick?
- MICK: What?

04:45.660 --> 04:50.206
My son has just taken romance
back into the Stone Ages.

04:50.415 --> 04:51.958
I'm with your mother.

04:52.125 --> 04:54.221
I think it's wonderful and romantic,

04:54.222 --> 04:56.921
and full of magic and lights and music.

04:57.088 --> 05:00.842
Megan, no. You promised you were
gonna keep the ceremony simple.

05:01.050 --> 05:02.510
Of course. Why wouldn't I?

05:02.677 --> 05:05.221
Because we O'Briens always
do everything over the top.

05:05.388 --> 05:08.266
But anything worth doing
is worth doing right.

05:08.891 --> 05:13.062
And on that note, let's keep
the vows short too, okay, Mom?

05:13.396 --> 05:14.647
Me?

05:14.814 --> 05:17.942
Why, I've always been
a woman of few words.

05:19.819 --> 05:21.487
[ALL LAUGHING]

05:21.654 --> 05:26.659
Okay, okay. I'll try to
keep it short too. Okay.

05:26.826 --> 05:28.536
Got room for one more?

05:28.745 --> 05:32.081
No, no, this is the big-people fire.
The kiddie fire's down the beach.

05:32.248 --> 05:33.541
That was very funny.

05:33.708 --> 05:35.168
MEGAN: So is Sarah coming?

05:35.335 --> 05:38.463
No, I just dropped her off at the
station. She has to work tonight.

05:38.629 --> 05:40.798
I'm surprised Connor
isn't here. I should call.

05:40.965 --> 05:43.634
I already did. He said he has to work.

05:43.968 --> 05:45.261
- Really?
- MEGAN: Mm-hm.

05:45.428 --> 05:48.306
I thought we had already
finished the paperwork...

05:50.516 --> 05:52.977
Yeah, no, he's probably
working on that other draft.

05:54.979 --> 05:56.230
Yeah.

05:56.606 --> 05:58.191
Well, now here's a toast.

05:58.649 --> 06:02.028
To Robin and Thomas for vows taken...

06:02.195 --> 06:04.739
and worth taking again.

06:04.989 --> 06:07.075
Here's to the O'Briens
love of making toasts.

06:07.492 --> 06:11.037
Here's to raising our spirits
and the glasses that hold them.

06:11.204 --> 06:13.873
Dad, did you just make a
toast about making toasts?

06:14.082 --> 06:16.584
- Yes, I did. I made it up.
- NELL: [LAUGHS]

06:16.751 --> 06:19.504
- That's a good one, sir.
- MEGAN: Cheers.

06:19.837 --> 06:20.838
[♪♪♪]

06:22.256 --> 06:24.509
ALEXANDRA: I don't remember
the last time I had a s'more.

06:24.675 --> 06:27.845
Well, my family are the
kings and queens of s'mores.

06:28.012 --> 06:29.012
In fact, if you ask my grandma,

06:29.015 --> 06:31.504
I think she'd tell you we invented them.

06:31.557 --> 06:33.810
It sounds nice, your family.

06:33.976 --> 06:35.812
Yeah.

06:35.978 --> 06:39.065
And when we fight, we fight hard...

06:39.440 --> 06:42.443
but we're pretty good
at making up. Eventually.

06:42.610 --> 06:46.656
- Like you and Jess?
- Yeah, like I said, eventually.

06:48.699 --> 06:50.785
Hey, I have a question.

06:50.952 --> 06:53.663
You work for your family business too.

06:53.830 --> 06:57.166
Why are your parents so set on David
running the company and not you?

06:57.333 --> 06:59.752
You went to Harvard Business School.

06:59.919 --> 07:02.171
It's a little more
complicated than that.

07:02.630 --> 07:04.173
Why?

07:05.007 --> 07:07.840
They've decided David's a
better fit to run the business,

07:07.841 --> 07:09.303
no matter what I say or do.

07:09.637 --> 07:12.765
It doesn't matter where I
went to school or what I know.

07:12.932 --> 07:15.685
When my parents make up their
mind, they never change it.

07:15.852 --> 07:17.228
But that...

07:18.187 --> 07:20.606
I mean, doesn't David get to have a say?

07:20.857 --> 07:22.900
You don't know my parents.

07:23.734 --> 07:27.238
Our family, we don't do eventually.

07:27.405 --> 07:29.490
We're more about never.

07:29.907 --> 07:31.826
[♪♪♪]

07:35.955 --> 07:38.374
Leiter and Norse agreed to
the merger before I left.

07:38.541 --> 07:41.169
We were just drawing
up contracts. I don't...

07:41.335 --> 07:46.424
Yeah. Okay, just send me the contracts
and I will take care of it here.

07:47.008 --> 07:48.217
Okay, thanks.

07:49.552 --> 07:51.596
Abby, you gotta see this.

07:52.054 --> 07:55.433
- Wow. Congratulations.
- LEIGH: Thanks, Abby.

07:55.641 --> 07:58.936
Nashville Country. I used to
read this when I was in pigtails.

07:59.103 --> 08:01.105
- Oh. I'd love to see that.
- [LAUGHS]

08:01.272 --> 08:03.399
- TRACE: Hey.
- LEIGH: Hey, how's our gear?

08:03.566 --> 08:05.735
Everything is stacked and stashed.

08:05.902 --> 08:08.946
Every day, Trace checks the
equipment after the roadies finish...

08:09.113 --> 08:11.073
and every day he says the same thing.

08:11.282 --> 08:14.243
I'm just used to doing it
myself. And I already looked.

08:14.452 --> 08:16.120
No mention of you and the girls.

08:16.287 --> 08:18.998
Ben wrote a good article,
most of it is even true.

08:19.165 --> 08:22.001
- Most of it?
- My life, abridged.

08:22.418 --> 08:23.586
Mostly the highlights...

08:23.753 --> 08:27.757
- with a few bumps along the way.
- MARK: That's what people wanna know.

08:27.965 --> 08:30.718
- You look good on that cover, Trace.
- Must be the lighting.

08:30.927 --> 08:32.385
- Must be.
- TRACE: [LAUGHS]

08:32.720 --> 08:35.389
Congrats on the show last
night, guys, and the article.

08:35.597 --> 08:39.559
It's big. And starting tonight,
you're doing another 10 minutes.

08:39.727 --> 08:41.562
Make sure you play something new.

08:41.729 --> 08:43.898
[CHUCKLES] No pressure.

08:44.065 --> 08:46.442
- MARK: It's only the beginning, Trace.
- That settles it.

08:46.609 --> 08:49.320
- We're playing "Bucky's Highway."
- JOHN: I vote "Wild and Free."

08:49.487 --> 08:51.155
LEIGH: What about "Bargains and Boots"?

08:51.364 --> 08:54.450
- We haven't played that.
- You okay? You don't look happy.

08:54.617 --> 08:57.787
No. I mean, it's amazing.

08:57.954 --> 09:01.374
But if we're getting 10 more
minutes, someone else is doing less.

09:01.749 --> 09:04.919
- Donovan?
- Looks like we just took part of his set.

09:05.127 --> 09:07.129
[♪♪♪]

09:12.051 --> 09:14.011
Working from home?

09:14.428 --> 09:18.140
Yeah, I'm planning my next
trip to Chicago on business.

09:18.432 --> 09:20.726
Seems the more time I spend at home...

09:20.893 --> 09:24.397
- the more I have to travel someplace else.
- Mm-hm.

09:24.605 --> 09:27.316
You know when it was that
Robin and Thomas first met?

09:27.483 --> 09:31.445
County fair. You and Thomas
spent at least $50 in quarters...

09:31.654 --> 09:34.407
trying to see who could win
the largest stuffed animal.

09:34.574 --> 09:37.785
That basketball rim was not
regulation size, let me tell you.

09:37.952 --> 09:40.997
I know, Mick, and you should have won.

09:41.163 --> 09:45.501
So you think maybe
a consolation prize...

09:45.668 --> 09:48.629
of a cinnamon roll might help?

09:53.718 --> 09:57.179
What? Why do you always think that
when someone gives you a gift...

09:57.388 --> 09:59.557
- they want something in return?
- It's true.

09:59.724 --> 10:02.935
Well, then I'm happy to
keep your streak alive.

10:06.981 --> 10:08.441
What do you think?

10:08.649 --> 10:11.944
Didn't Robin tell you she wanted
to keep the ceremony simple?

10:12.278 --> 10:15.406
Oh, yeah, that's what she said
but that's not what she meant.

10:16.991 --> 10:19.243
Mick O'Brien, when a
woman gets married...

10:19.452 --> 10:20.453
Renews her vows.

10:20.620 --> 10:22.300
And she tells you not
to go to any trouble,

10:22.301 --> 10:25.085
she's saying to go to all the trouble.

10:25.249 --> 10:26.876
[♪♪♪]

10:27.043 --> 10:29.629
Mick, you remember
when they got married?

10:29.795 --> 10:32.590
I was on bedrest with Bree...

10:32.757 --> 10:34.165
so I couldn't be maid of honor,

10:34.166 --> 10:37.678
I couldn't help, I couldn't even attend.

10:37.845 --> 10:42.933
So this time I just wanna do everything
I can to help make it go right.

10:44.477 --> 10:45.936
[MICK SIGHS]

10:46.729 --> 10:48.481
You know, this is very good.

10:48.648 --> 10:50.900
- Thanks.
- I was talking about the cinnamon roll.

10:51.067 --> 10:52.902
Of course you were.

10:53.527 --> 10:55.529
It's gonna take me a
few days to make this.

10:55.738 --> 10:57.823
- I know.
- And you know I actually work?

10:57.990 --> 11:01.702
- Oh, trust me, I know.
- And these lights are gonna take forever.

11:01.869 --> 11:04.622
Oh, don't worry about the
lights, I got them covered.

11:06.332 --> 11:08.334
[♪♪♪]

11:13.047 --> 11:14.256
I object.

11:15.091 --> 11:16.467
Overruled.

11:19.845 --> 11:21.263
Well...

11:21.430 --> 11:23.391
Kevin, Connor...

11:24.141 --> 11:29.730
your job is to hang all
these lights for the ceremony.

11:29.897 --> 11:32.233
Understood?

11:38.697 --> 11:40.991
I think that she's grounding us.

11:41.325 --> 11:44.870
- She's not allowed to do that, is she?
- I don't know. I'm too afraid to ask.

11:49.375 --> 11:51.710
So we'll just do this without talking?

11:53.546 --> 11:55.548
[♪♪♪]

11:57.925 --> 11:59.427
[SIGHS]

12:17.778 --> 12:18.821
- DAVID: What... ?
- Oops.

12:19.697 --> 12:20.781
Hello?

12:20.990 --> 12:23.409
- Down here.
- What are you doing?

12:23.617 --> 12:26.829
- I wanted to talk to you privately.
- Why didn't you knock on my door?

12:27.329 --> 12:29.957
I didn't wanna disturb
you while you were working.

12:30.166 --> 12:31.500
So you're...

12:34.628 --> 12:36.922
Okay, well, now I'm not working, so...

12:37.131 --> 12:40.551
Okay, I need to ask you something,
you don't have to answer right away...

12:40.718 --> 12:44.472
but by not answering, you're actually
answering, so you should answer.

12:44.763 --> 12:47.391
- So you should probably just ask.
- Okay.

12:47.558 --> 12:50.186
I just need to tell you that
if you want to stay here...

12:50.352 --> 12:53.105
because you're really good
at your job, I will be okay.

12:53.647 --> 12:56.484
But if you wanna come back with me...

12:57.026 --> 12:58.944
- that'll be fine too.
- Just fine?

12:59.278 --> 13:02.740
Fine as in amazing.
But it's your choice.

13:04.575 --> 13:08.537
Jess, ever since I became your chef...

13:08.704 --> 13:10.748
I only wanna be with you.

13:11.040 --> 13:12.625
Really?

13:13.501 --> 13:14.960
Great.

13:15.127 --> 13:17.963
Well, now that we have that
settled, I'll see you tonight?

13:18.422 --> 13:20.007
See you tonight.

13:20.466 --> 13:23.677
- Dude, if Romeo and Juliet...
- What about them?

13:23.844 --> 13:27.181
That's what this reminds me of,
Romeo and Juliet. You're Juliet.

13:27.389 --> 13:28.641
[♪♪♪]

13:28.807 --> 13:33.062
Romeo, Romeo, wherefore art thou, Romeo.

13:33.270 --> 13:34.939
I'm right here.

13:35.105 --> 13:37.399
Oh, this is so awesome.

13:37.816 --> 13:39.193
- Bye.
- [CHUCKLES] Bye.

13:46.283 --> 13:48.118
I thought we were going to eat.

13:48.285 --> 13:50.454
Don't worry, last time
I was out in 20 minutes.

13:50.621 --> 13:52.748
Shake some hands, give
a few sound bites...

13:52.915 --> 13:54.917
then we'll go to dinner, okay?

13:55.084 --> 13:58.671
Well, as your bodyguard, your
fans look excited to see you.

13:58.837 --> 14:00.798
You got my back, right?

14:00.965 --> 14:02.424
Always.

14:03.884 --> 14:06.387
I can't wait for you to
see the surprise I planned.

14:06.595 --> 14:07.596
A surprise?

14:07.763 --> 14:09.014
You're gonna love it.

14:09.181 --> 14:10.341
[CROWD SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY]

14:10.933 --> 14:12.101
TRACE: Hey.

14:12.685 --> 14:14.061
No problem.

14:17.690 --> 14:20.484
- Thanks.
- WOMAN: We love you so much.

14:20.776 --> 14:25.406
[♪♪♪]

14:28.617 --> 14:30.244
I got you something.

14:30.995 --> 14:33.789
I hate the fact that you think
bribery's gonna work on me.

14:34.123 --> 14:36.625
Because it does.

14:36.792 --> 14:39.211
I hate that you know
that too. What do we got?

14:39.420 --> 14:42.256
- Mm. Consider me bribed.
- [LAUGHS]

14:42.464 --> 14:44.133
And voilÃ .

14:44.425 --> 14:47.177
Oh, perfect. Another
picture, another arch.

14:47.344 --> 14:49.763
MEGAN: Mm-hm. I just
want it to be perfect.

14:49.972 --> 14:52.433
You know, I don't think
weddings need to be perfect.

14:52.600 --> 14:55.227
I mean, not that there's
anything bad about it...

14:55.394 --> 14:57.605
but it's just a day, and all the...

14:57.771 --> 14:59.550
All the speeches, the cake,

14:59.551 --> 15:02.110
the dancing seems like
a big deal at the time...

15:02.318 --> 15:04.570
- but they're not.
- Hmm. You enjoyed ours.

15:05.487 --> 15:10.242
Yeah, I just remember borrowing
money for a wedding ring...

15:10.409 --> 15:12.371
borrowing money for your wedding dress,

15:12.372 --> 15:14.204
borrowing for a first place to live.

15:14.413 --> 15:18.918
And we laughed that we had to find
something borrowed for the wedding.

15:19.126 --> 15:20.753
[LAUGHS]

15:20.920 --> 15:22.129
Nell's gloves.

15:24.256 --> 15:25.716
Yeah.

15:25.883 --> 15:27.885
[♪♪♪]

15:30.804 --> 15:32.473
Another one.

15:33.349 --> 15:34.350
TRACE: Make it two.

15:35.643 --> 15:37.186
Must be my lucky day.

15:37.353 --> 15:40.564
It's Trace Riley from
the Trace Riley Band.

15:40.731 --> 15:42.650
Listen, Donovan...

15:42.816 --> 15:45.945
- I want you to know...
- You didn't have anything to do with it?

15:47.613 --> 15:49.198
Yeah, I know.

15:50.449 --> 15:52.090
My guys overheard you talking to Mark,

15:52.091 --> 15:54.954
asking him not to give
you the extra time.

15:55.162 --> 15:56.789
I still don't feel right about it.

15:56.956 --> 16:00.709
I appreciate that, Trace,
but it ain't your doing.

16:00.876 --> 16:02.503
Mark...

16:03.170 --> 16:04.838
he's a smart man.

16:05.005 --> 16:07.132
Knows when he's got a hot hand.

16:07.299 --> 16:09.176
This is your time.

16:10.094 --> 16:11.512
What are you talking about?

16:12.221 --> 16:14.723
You know a funny thing about time?

16:15.057 --> 16:18.435
- You never think it's gonna run out.
- What do you mean by that?

16:18.644 --> 16:21.355
I used to look at my girl
the way you look at yours.

16:21.522 --> 16:25.025
Felt like nothing could
ever tear us apart.

16:26.485 --> 16:29.029
You ever think about
trying to get her back?

16:30.406 --> 16:33.158
That ship sailed a long time ago.

16:33.701 --> 16:35.661
What about your daughter?

16:36.453 --> 16:39.081
She hasn't spoken to me in two years.

16:41.166 --> 16:44.420
- Maybe it's time to fix that.
- Sometimes...

16:44.586 --> 16:48.048
you travel too far down the road to
just swing it around and head back.

16:48.549 --> 16:50.718
I think you can always go back.

16:50.884 --> 16:53.053
- Make it right.
- That's because...

16:53.220 --> 16:55.431
you still think you
got time on your side.

16:55.764 --> 17:00.269
One day you wake up and realize
you didn't lose it, you just...

17:00.644 --> 17:02.062
misplaced it.

17:07.859 --> 17:09.737
[♪♪♪]

17:09.903 --> 17:13.656
So David is going to leave
his job and come home with me.

17:13.824 --> 17:18.162
Well, not to my home, but to the
inn. Not to live, but to work.

17:18.328 --> 17:19.663
Has he told his parents yet?

17:19.829 --> 17:22.750
He said no. I'm thinking maybe.
That would explain the quiche.

17:22.915 --> 17:25.711
That quiche was such a
warning shot across the bow.

17:26.252 --> 17:27.253
Exactly.

17:27.421 --> 17:30.215
It's a complicated mixture
of David's parents...

17:30.382 --> 17:33.343
eggs, personal feelings, salt...

17:33.510 --> 17:36.138
- family obligations.
- Cooking temperatures, I got it.

17:36.305 --> 17:38.265
You gotta stop. Let that quiche go.

17:38.432 --> 17:41.727
That quiche is David's parents.
It's not David's quiche. We like his.

17:41.935 --> 17:43.812
Okay, true.

17:44.313 --> 17:46.648
- But I can't turn off my brain.
- I know.

17:46.815 --> 17:49.151
Neither can I, but David
wants to be with you...

17:49.318 --> 17:50.944
you wanna be with David.

17:51.111 --> 17:53.864
Life or quiche don't have to
be more complicated than that.

17:54.031 --> 17:56.658
- I know, but it always is, isn't it?
- Well...

17:57.076 --> 17:59.578
- We're still amazing though, right?
- Oh, amazing.

17:59.787 --> 18:01.163
Okay, I'm done here.

18:01.330 --> 18:03.832
- What?
- I'm having a G and T. Hi.

18:04.041 --> 18:05.626
[CHUCKLES]

18:05.918 --> 18:07.211
BREE: Oh, stop, stop, stop.

18:10.255 --> 18:12.800
You're sure we have
enough extension cords?

18:13.342 --> 18:14.885
Because...

18:15.552 --> 18:18.764
I could go out, get a couple more.

18:22.518 --> 18:24.686
You know, this will
go faster if we talked.

18:25.854 --> 18:27.278
You don't seem to
have a problem talking,

18:27.279 --> 18:30.234
whether anyone wants to listen.

18:31.026 --> 18:35.197
So, what is that? It's like
a dig? What are you, 12?

18:36.615 --> 18:38.832
You know, Connor, I'm so
sick and tired of this.

18:38.833 --> 18:41.537
I'm so sick and tired of you just...

18:41.703 --> 18:44.665
If this happened to me, even if
you were wrong, I'd wanna know.

18:44.832 --> 18:45.874
You weren't.

18:46.792 --> 18:49.795
- What?
- You weren't wrong, all right?

18:49.962 --> 18:52.673
The guy you saw with
Danielle was her ex-boyfriend.

18:52.881 --> 18:54.174
[♪♪♪]

18:54.341 --> 18:56.385
I guess that makes
you a little bit happy.

18:56.552 --> 18:59.429
Get to be the hero one more
time. Kevin saves the day again.

18:59.638 --> 19:02.141
You have no idea what
you're talking about.

19:07.771 --> 19:09.273
After not seeing each other...

19:09.439 --> 19:13.235
I can only imagine what you and
David have been talking about.

19:14.153 --> 19:18.073
Well, I'm not exactly sure either,
some of it was in iambic pentameter.

19:18.240 --> 19:19.491
[CHUCKLES]

19:19.658 --> 19:22.995
Well, Jessica, I know
my son really likes you.

19:23.162 --> 19:26.165
Really? That's great,
because I really like him.

19:26.331 --> 19:27.901
And I know that, to you,

19:27.902 --> 19:30.544
the idea of David running a
multi-million dollar corporation...

19:30.711 --> 19:34.381
which employs hundreds of
people isn't as important as...

19:34.548 --> 19:36.175
perhaps baking quiches.

19:36.383 --> 19:40.012
- We did talk about that.
- Which is why I'm asking you a favor.

19:40.179 --> 19:41.930
A favor? Absolutely.

19:42.097 --> 19:43.473
Good.

19:43.640 --> 19:46.560
Because you like David,
David seems to like you...

19:46.727 --> 19:49.563
- why don't you stay here with us?
- Here?

19:49.730 --> 19:52.524
Until you and David settle
down, and buy a home.

19:52.691 --> 19:56.278
I run a B and... Auberge
in Chesapeake Shores.

19:56.445 --> 19:57.905
I know you do, for now.

19:58.071 --> 20:01.867
I'm sure you can run one here in
Maine, or in Paris, or Boston...

20:02.034 --> 20:04.119
or any place you'd like, really.

20:04.286 --> 20:08.081
- Jessica, think of what's best for David.
- But...

20:08.248 --> 20:09.958
And it won't be so bad.

20:10.125 --> 20:13.337
Besides, attending the odd
glamorous party every now and then.

20:13.545 --> 20:15.214
And depending on what you decide...

20:15.380 --> 20:18.634
tonight's party could either be
a going-away affair for David...

20:19.259 --> 20:23.305
or a celebration of David
taking over Peck Enterprises.

20:23.472 --> 20:25.682
And welcoming you to
the family, of course.

20:25.891 --> 20:27.267
[♪♪♪]

20:27.434 --> 20:30.062
And it's up to me to make that decision?

20:30.270 --> 20:32.105
In the meantime...

20:32.272 --> 20:33.512
please accept this small gift

20:33.513 --> 20:36.902
for being so kind and
gracious to our son.

20:38.904 --> 20:42.115
Jessica, you know what
happened to the girl...

20:42.282 --> 20:44.993
who became a princess
when she found her prince?

20:46.245 --> 20:48.330
She lived happily ever after?

20:49.248 --> 20:50.415
[CHUCKLES]

20:53.669 --> 20:55.629
Thank you.

20:55.796 --> 20:57.422
What?

21:00.842 --> 21:04.012
Trace, I've called the girls, but
I still have work calls to make.

21:04.179 --> 21:06.765
If this merger falls through,
it's gonna be terrible...

21:06.932 --> 21:08.801
Abby, you've been on the phone all day,

21:08.802 --> 21:11.353
I'm sure your deal
can wait until morning.

21:11.520 --> 21:14.523
And besides, I'm trying
to be romantic here.

21:14.690 --> 21:17.317
- What? By kidnapping me?
- If that's what it takes.

21:17.484 --> 21:18.610
[ABBY CHUCKLES]

21:18.777 --> 21:20.112
You have any idea where we are?

21:20.279 --> 21:21.321
[SIGHS]

21:22.030 --> 21:23.845
Well, it's been quiet
since we left the hotel,

21:23.846 --> 21:26.243
so I'm hoping we're finally alone.

21:26.410 --> 21:28.578
Well, you're right about that.

21:28.870 --> 21:34.543
How about I give you a clue?
We are surrounded by flowers.

21:34.751 --> 21:36.336
[SNIFFING]

21:36.503 --> 21:37.879
I do not smell flowers.

21:38.046 --> 21:39.464
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

21:41.341 --> 21:44.344
[♪♪♪]

21:51.810 --> 21:55.439
Trace, this is the Alkin Gallery.
How are we here after hours?

21:55.605 --> 21:57.482
I had our stage manager make a call...

21:57.649 --> 22:01.737
let them know we have a very
passionate fan of impressionist art.

22:02.612 --> 22:03.739
Seriously?

22:03.947 --> 22:06.533
It also helped that he's
married to the curator's sister.

22:06.700 --> 22:08.118
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

22:12.539 --> 22:14.291
What do you think?

22:15.667 --> 22:18.295
You have managed to combine...

22:18.462 --> 22:20.630
- my three favorite things.
- Uh...

22:20.797 --> 22:24.343
Me, impressionist art and...

22:24.509 --> 22:26.511
- Cheese.
- Cheese, of course.

22:26.678 --> 22:28.555
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

22:29.931 --> 22:31.391
[ABBY SIGHS]

22:34.603 --> 22:37.856
Trace, are you gonna be happy
without all of this back home?

22:38.023 --> 22:39.983
We have cheese back home.

22:40.901 --> 22:42.694
[TRACE CHUCKLES]

22:42.861 --> 22:46.907
No, without the thousands of
fans screaming your name...

22:47.115 --> 22:49.367
and the VIP treatment.

22:50.911 --> 22:52.579
Abby...

22:53.747 --> 22:56.875
none of that means anything
if I don't have you.

23:00.837 --> 23:03.840
- You've been practicing that line?
- Yeah, a bit.

23:04.007 --> 23:06.176
[BOTH LAUGH]

23:06.635 --> 23:10.764
We do have permission to be in
here, right? We didn't just break in?

23:10.931 --> 23:13.050
We might have. If you hear something,

23:13.051 --> 23:15.852
grab a Monet, and
we'll make a run for it.

23:16.061 --> 23:17.729
[LAUGHS]

23:18.814 --> 23:21.024
- Cheers.
- Cheers.

23:26.988 --> 23:29.991
It might be the most
beautiful thing I've ever seen.

23:30.158 --> 23:32.393
It's so beautiful that
other beautiful things

23:32.394 --> 23:34.371
realize their beauty doesn't compare...

23:34.955 --> 23:36.757
making other beautiful things feel bad

23:36.758 --> 23:39.793
for thinking they were ever beautiful.

23:39.960 --> 23:44.631
- It's vindictively beautiful.
- Spitefully beautiful.

23:44.798 --> 23:46.925
It's just cruel.

23:48.844 --> 23:50.095
[BREE SIGHS]

23:50.637 --> 23:55.225
You know, I always thought
life should be like this.

23:55.392 --> 23:58.687
- Being in the Peck summer home?
- No.

23:58.854 --> 24:03.400
Lying around with my
sisters on a warm day...

24:03.567 --> 24:05.944
doing nothing at all.

24:06.236 --> 24:08.280
And staring at criminally
beautiful dresses.

24:08.446 --> 24:11.491
- Swaying in the breeze.
- You write about things like this.

24:11.658 --> 24:15.829
I know, mostly because I can't
actually bring myself to do nothing.

24:16.788 --> 24:19.916
- But you're doing it now.
- I know.

24:22.836 --> 24:24.880
So David's mother asked you to stay?

24:27.090 --> 24:31.219
So David will run the
family's corporation...

24:31.386 --> 24:34.347
and I will run an auberge in France.

24:36.141 --> 24:39.728
- You'll have to learn to speak French.
- Oui.

24:40.854 --> 24:45.317
- You'll be leaving Chesapeake Shores.
- Oui.

24:47.652 --> 24:51.156
And we will be wearing
these beautiful dresses.

24:51.740 --> 24:53.491
- "We," right?
- Hmm.

24:54.284 --> 24:55.702
Oui.

24:57.662 --> 24:59.247
[BOTH SIGH]

25:00.457 --> 25:02.459
Is that what you want?

25:05.170 --> 25:07.422
Well, I think I'm in love.

25:08.632 --> 25:11.384
And I wanna do what's best for him.

25:12.177 --> 25:16.890
And me coming here would mean that...

25:17.599 --> 25:19.976
he wouldn't have to leave...

25:20.936 --> 25:23.730
and I could still run an auberge.

25:25.148 --> 25:28.235
But I've never left
Chesapeake Shores before.

25:29.611 --> 25:31.613
[♪♪♪]

25:33.365 --> 25:35.533
I'll visit often.

25:36.243 --> 25:38.203
I know you will.

25:42.332 --> 25:44.834
[BOTH BREATHE DEEPLY]

25:45.001 --> 25:46.753
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

25:47.879 --> 25:51.675
MEGAN: Oh, these are gorgeous.
- I told you to keep it small.

25:52.092 --> 25:53.969
- And I ignored you.
- Ugh.

25:54.135 --> 25:55.428
[CHUCKLES]

25:55.637 --> 25:57.555
- So you nervous?
- Hardly.

25:57.722 --> 25:59.933
I'm already married.

26:00.183 --> 26:02.727
Oh, I do love Thomas.

26:03.311 --> 26:05.480
I have people come into my practice,

26:05.481 --> 26:08.150
and they've been married 50 years...

26:08.316 --> 26:13.488
and things changed from where
they start. The marriage changes.

26:13.655 --> 26:17.158
But they've just managed
to find a way to get closer.

26:17.325 --> 26:19.828
- A different way, you know?
- Hm.

26:20.662 --> 26:22.789
- Those are pretty.
- You know...

26:22.956 --> 26:24.620
they say that sometimes
it takes a lifetime

26:24.621 --> 26:26.960
to learn how to dance together.

26:27.210 --> 26:30.714
I'm just hoping that
the way we are now...

26:30.880 --> 26:33.034
will be different than
all the other times

26:33.035 --> 26:34.760
that just did not work before.

26:35.635 --> 26:38.179
- A second chance. Yep.
- New beginnings.

26:38.388 --> 26:40.473
With way, way too many flowers.

26:40.640 --> 26:43.893
Trust me, you're gonna
love it. They're gorgeous.

26:44.352 --> 26:48.481
That's all I'm asking, Mort.
Just consider the deal. Okay.

26:48.648 --> 26:50.692
- I was right, wasn't I?
- You were.

26:50.859 --> 26:53.862
They're back to being friends,
the merger's back on. For now.

26:54.029 --> 26:56.948
Which means you can resume
your bodyguard duties.

26:57.115 --> 27:00.327
I gotta tell you, a woman's been
following me around all week.

27:00.493 --> 27:02.370
- Oh, really?
- She's relentless.

27:02.537 --> 27:05.081
She even followed me into
a closed museum last night.

27:05.248 --> 27:06.833
Wow, that sounds serious.

27:07.000 --> 27:08.835
[BOTH LAUGH]

27:09.002 --> 27:12.339
I'm sorry, are you Trace
Riley? Can I take a picture?

27:13.006 --> 27:16.009
- Sure. What's your name?
- Diane.

27:16.217 --> 27:19.137
- Nice to meet you, Diane.
- You too, Abby.

27:20.430 --> 27:21.639
Join us for a photo?

27:22.015 --> 27:24.184
- I'm sorry, do I know you?
- Well, no.

27:25.060 --> 27:26.853
Diane, how... ? How do you know Abby?

27:27.062 --> 27:28.438
[SOFTLY] Oh.

27:31.524 --> 27:34.235
DIANE: You have a beautiful family.

27:34.236 --> 27:35.972
_

27:36.020 --> 27:37.822
[♪♪♪]

27:40.909 --> 27:43.870
THOMAS: Typical of your dad, he
makes the decision to do something...

27:44.037 --> 27:46.581
and then has other people
actually do the work.

27:46.790 --> 27:48.353
Dad has this way of convincing people

27:48.354 --> 27:50.380
when they're doing something for him...

27:50.543 --> 27:52.545
they're really doing it for themselves.

27:52.796 --> 27:56.174
Man, he was a tough act to follow.

27:56.341 --> 27:58.468
I had this one teacher, Mr. Healy.

27:58.635 --> 28:01.930
Never did learn my name, spent the
whole year calling me "Mick Two."

28:02.138 --> 28:04.808
- Well, it must've been tough.
- Following a big brother...

28:04.974 --> 28:08.228
who everyone knew was gonna
be a success, including him?

28:08.395 --> 28:09.938
Yeah.

28:11.189 --> 28:14.984
You know, my life hasn't
exactly been easy either.

28:16.986 --> 28:21.741
It's hard to see that until
you're out of the shadow.

28:21.950 --> 28:24.536
And that takes time.

28:25.412 --> 28:28.665
Thing is, I wouldn't be doing what
I'm doing if Mick wasn't so good...

28:28.832 --> 28:30.041
at what he does.

28:30.250 --> 28:31.376
[CHUCKLES]

28:31.543 --> 28:35.588
Okay, so you battling Dad over
the trust is really Dad's fault?

28:36.631 --> 28:37.924
In a way.

28:38.883 --> 28:41.511
Hey, truth is...

28:41.678 --> 28:44.973
we're all just trying to
find a way to be special.

28:45.181 --> 28:47.183
[♪♪♪]

28:48.435 --> 28:49.769
Here.

28:54.774 --> 28:57.610
- I could've done this myself, you know.
- MICK: I know.

28:58.611 --> 29:01.740
You know, I threatened our mayor
once. We were back at school.

29:02.115 --> 29:03.700
He really hated Thomas.

29:03.908 --> 29:06.286
- Is this story going anywhere?
- Eventually.

29:06.494 --> 29:07.537
[MICK CHUCKLES]

29:07.704 --> 29:10.039
- I assume Thomas didn't vote for him?
- Probably not.

29:10.206 --> 29:12.292
It was an after-school basketball game.

29:12.500 --> 29:15.545
Thomas always tried to avoid
fights, and Frank went after him.

29:15.754 --> 29:18.840
- So I got involved.
- What'd you do?

29:19.883 --> 29:20.884
I got in his face...

29:21.050 --> 29:24.554
and I told him if he messed with my
brother, he'd have to mess with me.

29:24.721 --> 29:26.473
So you threatened him? That's great.

29:26.806 --> 29:29.934
You could call it that, or I
was sticking up for my brother.

29:30.602 --> 29:33.563
And then Thomas wouldn't
speak to me for a month.

29:33.897 --> 29:36.232
Well, in our family a month is nothing.

29:36.399 --> 29:39.778
It has taken us 40 years to
figure out why we weren't speaking.

29:41.571 --> 29:43.573
[♪♪♪]

29:48.453 --> 29:52.290
- I can't wait for tomorrow night.
- Neither can I.

29:53.041 --> 29:56.127
Jess O'Brien, would you dance with me?

29:56.336 --> 29:57.378
[PLAYING CLASSICAL MUSIC]

29:57.545 --> 30:00.757
David Peck, I would
love to dance with you.

30:00.924 --> 30:02.592
[CHUCKLES]

30:07.806 --> 30:09.766
This is a big step.

30:10.975 --> 30:16.648
You said being with me was an
adventure, so why not just take one?

30:18.358 --> 30:21.486
But I'd... I'd never
ask you to move for me.

30:21.653 --> 30:23.738
That's why I want to.

30:24.155 --> 30:26.032
Are you nervous?

30:28.868 --> 30:31.785
Um... Running the company temporarily

30:31.786 --> 30:34.040
is a lot different than permanently.

30:34.207 --> 30:36.125
Or running away.

30:38.127 --> 30:40.004
- Together.
- [CHUCKLES]

31:08.074 --> 31:11.160
Abby, it's an obscure
website, and it'll pass.

31:11.327 --> 31:13.705
That's not the point, this is my family.

31:13.913 --> 31:16.583
I know, and I know you didn't
sign up for any of this...

31:16.749 --> 31:18.740
but they get this first
shot, and then they move on.

31:18.741 --> 31:20.545
And it's not a story.

31:20.962 --> 31:23.506
You don't know that,
and it might get worse.

31:23.715 --> 31:26.050
ANNOUNCER: Give it up for
one of the hottest bands.

31:26.217 --> 31:29.596
Celebrating their new
record, it's Trace Riley...

31:29.762 --> 31:33.641
Abby, it's gonna be fine. Let's
just talk about this later.

31:33.850 --> 31:35.727
[CHEERS AND APPLAUSE]

31:38.730 --> 31:40.732
[LOUDER CHEERS AND APPLAUSE]

31:42.817 --> 31:44.903
How are you doing tonight, Dallas?

31:51.034 --> 31:53.870
[♪♪♪]

31:54.579 --> 31:57.206
THOMAS: Mick, maybe you're
not completely clear...

31:57.373 --> 31:59.500
on how bachelor parties work...

31:59.667 --> 32:01.485
but normally, the groom
doesn't have to work

32:01.486 --> 32:03.463
for three hours to get a beer.

32:03.630 --> 32:06.090
MICK: What's the matter,
you don't like it?

32:06.299 --> 32:07.967
No, it's fine.

32:08.134 --> 32:10.803
I just don't think you
understand the concept of a party.

32:10.970 --> 32:13.306
Oh, I understand the concept of a party.

32:13.473 --> 32:15.975
I'm the guy who used to
close the joint, remember?

32:16.225 --> 32:17.375
I'm just a little greedy

32:17.376 --> 32:20.772
to get this baby out on the
high seas as soon as possible.

32:22.065 --> 32:26.110
So now I have to ask. Am I the
only one who knows about this boat?

32:26.402 --> 32:27.779
Yeah.

32:27.987 --> 32:29.614
Any reason why?

32:29.864 --> 32:31.824
I have no idea.

32:31.991 --> 32:33.451
I didn't intend to tell you.

32:33.660 --> 32:35.119
[CHUCKLES]

32:35.453 --> 32:37.622
You know what I find amazing?

32:38.373 --> 32:40.102
You've made a mess of so many things,

32:40.103 --> 32:42.961
yet you managed to
raise five great kids.

32:44.087 --> 32:47.507
Yeah, thank you, and I
find it amazing that...

32:47.674 --> 32:51.010
even though the O'Briens have
never been very good at marriage...

32:51.177 --> 32:54.180
you're still working
on yours after 30 years.

32:54.514 --> 32:57.308
An O'Brien happily married,
that would be interesting.

32:57.475 --> 32:58.935
It'd be a miracle. Heh.

33:00.103 --> 33:03.606
- Kind of like this boat not sinking.
- Exactly.

33:07.485 --> 33:10.530
- No, you don't have to pay me for the beer.
- Oh, no.

33:13.700 --> 33:15.702
MICK: Queen Victoria?

33:16.786 --> 33:18.162
1888?

33:20.623 --> 33:23.876
This is the coin that Dad put
under the mast when he stepped it.

33:24.585 --> 33:26.379
[♪♪♪]

33:26.546 --> 33:27.546
When he got rid of the boat

33:27.564 --> 33:31.255
and they pulled the mast
out, I kept the coin.

33:34.178 --> 33:36.848
It was the only time we all got along.

33:37.056 --> 33:40.101
The only time I ever saw him relaxed.

33:40.727 --> 33:43.396
It's the only time I
ever saw him smiling.

33:44.814 --> 33:49.235
And now you've got a coin
looking for another boat.

33:49.944 --> 33:52.280
Wow, this is...

34:01.706 --> 34:03.666
Thank you, Thomas. Thank you.

34:08.545 --> 34:10.339
You gonna need a crew.

34:14.469 --> 34:17.221
Well, then, to the ship, to the crew...

34:17.804 --> 34:21.225
- and the Blue Lady of the Skies.
- And the Blue Lady of the Skies.

34:21.391 --> 34:23.518
MICK: No idea what Dad meant by that.
- Not a clue.

34:23.686 --> 34:26.438
- I don't think he even knew.
- I don't think he knew either.

34:26.981 --> 34:29.775
Yeah. I... I know, girls.

34:29.942 --> 34:34.280
I understand, sweetie. Well, I
am going to see you very soon.

34:35.864 --> 34:40.495
I love you too. I love
you both so much. Okay.

34:41.496 --> 34:42.621
[BEEP]

34:45.458 --> 34:47.126
[SIGHS]

34:56.302 --> 34:58.346
- Hi.
- Hi.

34:59.931 --> 35:02.266
- What's this?
- I've been going back and forth...

35:02.433 --> 35:04.727
but I had to show you this.

35:07.480 --> 35:09.398
What is this?

35:12.193 --> 35:13.945
Mortgage?

35:14.570 --> 35:15.780
School reports?

35:15.947 --> 35:18.533
I found it in my dad's office.

35:21.077 --> 35:22.411
This is Jess' entire life.

35:23.538 --> 35:28.209
Like I said, when it comes to my
parents, nothing happens by accident.

35:32.338 --> 35:33.881
Thank you.

35:35.383 --> 35:37.385
[♪♪♪]

35:50.314 --> 35:51.524
Good book?

35:53.818 --> 35:56.821
Yeah, but I've read better.

35:56.988 --> 35:58.531
It's pretty slow.

36:02.618 --> 36:05.037
Do you remember your
plastic army soldiers?

36:07.456 --> 36:08.791
What?

36:08.958 --> 36:13.254
That giant box of green soldiers?

36:14.172 --> 36:15.882
And they all melted?

36:19.051 --> 36:22.805
- That might've been me.
- Mm.

36:22.972 --> 36:26.559
- So you were the one.
- Yeah. Yeah.

36:26.767 --> 36:31.230
I borrowed Dad's video
camera with my friends.

36:31.397 --> 36:34.025
We sort of shot a war movie.

36:34.442 --> 36:36.235
Might have lit them on fire.

36:36.402 --> 36:38.070
[KEVIN CHUCKLES]

36:38.237 --> 36:42.033
All right, and you're
telling me this now, why?

36:44.660 --> 36:47.371
When you told me about Danielle...

36:49.290 --> 36:51.542
Look, I can take care of myself...

36:52.501 --> 36:55.880
but you were just trying to help...

36:56.047 --> 36:58.716
and I...

37:00.801 --> 37:02.178
[♪♪♪]

37:02.345 --> 37:03.346
I'm sorry.

37:06.641 --> 37:10.228
Anyway, I thought maybe
I could make it up to you.

37:10.394 --> 37:14.065
You know, brothers in arms...

37:14.649 --> 37:16.317
band of brothers.

37:18.986 --> 37:21.864
It's a medic. A little Kevin.

37:22.365 --> 37:25.701
This might be one of the
weirder things you've done.

37:25.952 --> 37:30.039
- Although this guy does look like me.
- [LAUGHS] Yeah, that's what I thought.

37:36.254 --> 37:38.506
- Thanks.
- Yeah.

37:39.340 --> 37:41.592
That's me on the stretcher.

37:41.801 --> 37:43.678
[BOTH LAUGH]

37:46.013 --> 37:47.682
ABBY: Can't believe
we're saying goodbye.

37:47.848 --> 37:50.142
I know it's just for a
few weeks this time, but...

37:50.309 --> 37:52.937
TRACE: But it's supposed
to get easier, not harder.

37:53.104 --> 37:54.438
Yeah.

37:56.399 --> 37:58.317
So we'll talk tonight?

37:58.985 --> 38:00.861
I will call you when I get in.

38:02.113 --> 38:04.156
Thanks for being my bodyguard.

38:04.824 --> 38:07.034
Well, someone's gotta have your back.

38:08.119 --> 38:09.954
Listen, Abby.

38:10.579 --> 38:12.415
- I'm so sorry.
- I know.

38:14.333 --> 38:15.334
I love you.

38:18.421 --> 38:19.630
I love you too.

38:24.468 --> 38:25.761
Come on.

38:27.263 --> 38:28.806
- Bye.
- Bye.

38:29.015 --> 38:30.349
[CAMERA CLICKS]

38:38.232 --> 38:39.650
[SIGHS]

38:43.279 --> 38:45.406
Jess, this is crazy. I'm so sorry.

38:45.614 --> 38:47.700
- JESS: I'm not.
- You're not sorry?

38:47.867 --> 38:49.785
I'm too upset to be sorry.

38:50.328 --> 38:53.164
And to think I thought Deidra liked me.

38:53.497 --> 38:56.792
I thought she truly wanted the
best for me. The best for David.

38:57.001 --> 39:00.963
- Jess, you look really good in that dress.
- Really?

39:02.465 --> 39:04.925
- I'm not gonna take it!
- Okay, what are you gonna do?

39:05.092 --> 39:06.844
I don't know. Everything.

39:07.053 --> 39:10.556
Nothing, I don't know. I'm
just very, very, very angry.

39:10.723 --> 39:12.433
Do you want me to come with you?

39:12.600 --> 39:15.644
No, I want you to stay
here and stick to the plan.

39:15.811 --> 39:19.690
Got it. You're not going to
do anything too crazy, right?

39:20.024 --> 39:22.443
Have I ever done anything
crazy in my lifetime?

39:22.610 --> 39:24.820
- Frequently.
- Then yes, I am.

39:25.237 --> 39:26.697
[ABBY GRUNTS]

39:27.865 --> 39:29.241
[HUFFS]

39:32.370 --> 39:33.871
Mr. and Mrs. Peck.

39:35.915 --> 39:39.752
- You look lovely, Jessica.
- Thank you, I know.

39:39.919 --> 39:41.253
You look lovely too.

39:41.462 --> 39:42.755
Oh, thank you.

39:42.963 --> 39:44.882
Which is why this hurts so much.

39:46.550 --> 39:49.095
You had no right to spy on me.

39:49.261 --> 39:54.266
This is just not cool, and
mean, and rotten and wrong.

39:54.475 --> 39:57.978
Jessica, there is a complete
explanation for all of this.

39:58.187 --> 40:00.981
Really? Oh, good.

40:01.190 --> 40:03.192
[♪♪♪]

40:03.692 --> 40:05.736
I mean, no. This is just wrong.

40:06.904 --> 40:08.390
We wanted to make sure that

40:08.391 --> 40:10.991
David was with someone
of whom we approve.

40:11.575 --> 40:14.537
Still wrong. You can't spy on me.

40:15.287 --> 40:17.248
I don't see the problem, Jessica.

40:18.624 --> 40:20.876
And that's the problem.

40:21.544 --> 40:25.131
You say that you want me here, you
tell David that you want me here...

40:25.297 --> 40:28.050
and all the while, it's
to see if I'm good enough?

40:29.552 --> 40:32.221
Yeah, I might just run a B&B...

40:32.388 --> 40:36.308
and I really don't know what an
auberge is, and I don't speak French...

40:36.475 --> 40:38.102
and I don't play polo...

40:38.269 --> 40:40.350
and when you said "Gstaad" earlier,

40:40.351 --> 40:41.897
I didn't know it started with a "G."

40:42.064 --> 40:43.941
Which is silly anyway.

40:44.692 --> 40:46.232
But I am proud of who I am,

40:46.233 --> 40:48.696
and where I come from,
and who my family is...

40:48.863 --> 40:51.210
and while they're all nuts,
and we have our problems,

40:51.211 --> 40:52.783
trust me, a ton of them...

40:53.784 --> 40:55.705
they love me, and I love them,

40:55.706 --> 40:58.664
and I don't need you to
say I'm good enough...

40:58.831 --> 41:02.334
because no one is gonna
put Jess in a corner.

41:04.128 --> 41:07.548
So before I move into this fishbowl...

41:07.715 --> 41:13.262
I'm leaving, and that's
I, Jess. Not I, Jessica.

41:14.555 --> 41:19.602
So you can have your party,
and your life, and your son...

41:19.768 --> 41:22.480
even though I love him a whole lot...

41:23.689 --> 41:25.483
but you can't have me.

41:26.525 --> 41:29.236
And I'm keeping this dress.

41:29.737 --> 41:30.988
[♪♪♪]

41:31.489 --> 41:32.823
[JESS PANTING]

41:41.749 --> 41:45.169
- You're wearing your dress too?
- You bet I am, I'm never taking it off.

41:45.336 --> 41:48.464
Operation Pumpkin, engaged.

41:50.090 --> 41:53.427
- You look really amazing by the way.
- Really? Thank you so much.

41:53.594 --> 41:55.095
[GRUNTS]

42:03.187 --> 42:05.481
- JESS: You tell David we're leaving?
- Haven't seen him.

42:05.648 --> 42:08.108
- JESS: What? But that was part of the plan.
- No time.

42:08.275 --> 42:09.902
JESS: Oh, no.

42:20.454 --> 42:22.456
[♪♪♪]

42:30.839 --> 42:34.843
NELL: Love is a spark
that creates a fire...

42:35.010 --> 42:37.555
and to make it last,
you have to tend to it.

42:37.721 --> 42:41.058
You have to nurture it. And you
have to give it room to grow.

42:41.267 --> 42:43.321
It's about changing with each other,

42:43.322 --> 42:45.646
and it's about finding the balance.

42:45.813 --> 42:50.776
Not only who you are,
but who you are together.

42:50.985 --> 42:53.862
You enter marriage with
your eyes wide open...

42:54.488 --> 42:57.700
but you walk through
it with one eye shut.

42:57.866 --> 43:02.162
Because great marriages, they
don't worry about the small things.

43:02.580 --> 43:07.293
No, great marriages, they
focus on the bigger picture...

43:07.501 --> 43:09.753
and they focus on love.

43:12.339 --> 43:13.549
Kiss her now?

43:14.049 --> 43:18.554
You may kiss each other. Kiss
your wife, and kiss your husband.

43:19.763 --> 43:21.765
[BREE WHOOPING]

43:23.017 --> 43:25.311
MICK: Well done.
Congratulations, Thomas.

43:26.520 --> 43:29.064
- NELL: Oh, Thomas.
- MEGAN: Congratulations.

43:29.690 --> 43:31.859
KEVIN: Guys, congratulations.

43:35.988 --> 43:37.990
[CHEERS AND APPLAUSE]

43:42.870 --> 43:45.164
You've been amazing, San Antonio.

43:46.165 --> 43:48.208
We've got time for one more.

43:48.375 --> 43:50.544
It's called "More Where That Came From."

43:52.004 --> 43:53.464
One, two, three.

43:58.052 --> 44:02.806
♪ They love to tell us ♪
♪ That we'll never make it ♪

44:02.973 --> 44:07.186
♪ They're throwing stones ♪
♪ Against the glass just to break it ♪

44:08.145 --> 44:10.564
♪ But they don't live here ♪

44:10.731 --> 44:16.195
♪ They don't know this kind of love ♪

44:20.532 --> 44:23.327
MEGAN: Thank you for building that arch.

44:23.494 --> 44:25.162
Twice.

44:26.413 --> 44:27.915
Oh, you were right.

44:28.082 --> 44:30.501
I'm glad we didn't keep it simple.

44:30.959 --> 44:34.880
- "If it's worth doing, it's worth doing right."
- Nicely done.

44:35.047 --> 44:37.174
- Ah. Years of practice.
- [CHUCKLES]

44:38.801 --> 44:43.097
At our wedding, did the
minister say that thing about...

44:43.263 --> 44:45.557
walking into a marriage
with both eyes open...

44:45.724 --> 44:48.686
and walking through
it with one eye closed?

44:49.978 --> 44:51.688
Honestly...

44:53.148 --> 44:54.483
I can't remember.

44:54.650 --> 44:56.652
[♪♪♪]

45:45.576 --> 45:47.053
NARRATOR: Next time
on Chesapeake Shores:

45:47.077 --> 45:48.620
Simon, what are you doing here?

45:48.829 --> 45:52.666
- I volunteered to simplify your life.
- My parents still go out on dates too.

45:52.833 --> 45:55.627
ABBY: Okay, there are pictures
of my daughters online.

45:55.794 --> 45:58.922
- Trace, it scares me.
- I want to spend time with you.

45:59.089 --> 46:02.134
- And I'm not interested.
- I can't believe David and I are over.

46:02.301 --> 46:03.594
- I'll be there.
- What is it?

46:03.760 --> 46:06.472
Sarah was hurt at work. She's
on her way to the hospital.

